sec.p:
C. houaphanensis is most similar to C. chauquangensis (
Hoang et al . 2007
)
from Vietnam but can be distinguished from the latter by its smaller SVL , fewer infralabials and the presence of an internasal which is absent in C. chauquangensis . The genetic distance between them is approximately 11.6%. The molecular phylogenetic analysis showed Cyrtodactylus houaphanensis to be sister to C. puhuensis from Vietnam . The genetic distance is at least 3.3% but morphologically these taxa are clearly distinguishable by their different dorsal pattern (irregular, transverse bands in C. houaphanensis vs. thin, mostly clear, whitish, dorsal bands in C. puhuensis ) (
), the number of precloacal pores in males ( 6 in the new species vs. 5 inC. puhuensis ) and in particular by the femoral scale condition (not enlarged in the new species vs. enlarged in C. puhuensis ) (
Nguyen et al. 2014
). Moreover, the type locality of Cyrtodactylus houaphanensis near Viengxai, Houaphan Province , Laos is roughly 70 km from the type locality of C. puhuensis in Pu Hu
Nature Reserve, Thanh Hoa Province , Vietnam . C. houaphanensis is currently known only from the type locality and represents the first reported species of the genus Cyrtodactylus from Houaphan Province.

The karst forests, as the preferred habitat for Cyrtodactylus , have been shown to promote the speciation of the genus and harbor a high number of newly discovered species (Nguyen et al . 2015;
Luu et al . 2016a
;
Grismer et al . 2018
). The two karst related species described in this study from the northern highlands of Laos further illustrate the importance of this habitat type and expand the number of Laotian species included in the C. wayakonei group from three to five karst dwelling species, namely Cyrtodactylus houaphanensis , C. ngoiensis , C. spelaeus , C. wayakonei and C. vilaphongi .

Furthermore, the distribution of the species group is expanded herein within the northern highlands of Laos . The three species, which are members of the C. wayakonei group in
Luu et al. (2016a)
, C. spelaeus , C. wayakonei and C. vilaphongi , occur in the central and western areas of northern Laos , whereas the two new species were discovered in the eastern border of northern Laos (
). In contrast to the karst formations of Khammouane Province with a high density of species occurring in a small area, the northern species do not occur sympatrically since the five taxa inhabit four geographically separated provinces (
). Although these species are allopatrically distributed, they show a high level of similarity in morphology.

Based on the new discoveries, the list of Cyrtodactylus known from Laos is extended herein from 23 to 25 species (after
Uetz et al . 2020
) widely distributed across the country (
). Since a high level of species diversity of Cyrtodactylus has been recorded in adjacent countries like Vietnam (43 species) and Thailand (36 species) (
Uetz et al . 2020
), it is likely that additional species will be discovered in Laos , especially in the border areas.
